'''''Jedi Apprentice: The Shattered Peace''''' by [[Jude Watson]] is the tenth in a series of young reader novels called '''''[[Star Wars: Jedi Apprentice]]'''''. All the books in the series are written by [[Jude Watson]], except for the first book, [[Jedi Apprentice: The Rising Force|''The Rising Force'']], which was written by [[Dave Wolverton]]. The series explores the adventures of [[Qui-Gon Jinn/Legends|Qui-Gon Jinn]] and [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] prior to [[Star Wars: Episode I The Phantom Menace|''Star Wars'': Episode I ''The Phantom Menace'']].

==Publisher's summary==
<div align="center">'''Peace over Anger<br />Honor over Hate<br />Strength over Fear'''</div>

''For generations, the firstborn children of the rulers of the planet Rutan and the moon Senali have been exchanged at the age of seven. This was meant to promote peace and understanding between the societies. Now it has led them to the brink of war.''

''Leed, the heir to the Rutan throne, does not want to return to his home planet. His father will stop at nothing to get him back. Qui-Gon Jinn and Obi-Wan Kenobi must prevent this rift from turning to bloodshed.''

''It is their hardest challenge yet.''

==Plot summary==
[[Rutan/Legends|Rutan]] long ruled over its [[Moon/Legends|moon]] [[Senali]] before the [[Senali (species)|Senali]] managed to defeat them and drove them off their [[Planet/Legends|world]]. Afterwards, the two made peace, and it was agreed that the rulers would send their eldest [[Youngling/Legends|children]] to the other world at the age of seven and they would stay there until they turned sixteen.

[[Prince/Legends|Prince]] [[Leed]], however, refuses to return to Rutan. His [[Parent/Legends|father]] [[King/Legends|King]] [[Frane]] believes he was [[Brainwashing|brainwashed]] or threatened, and he will go to war unless his son is returned. [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] and [[Qui-Gon Jinn/Legends|Qui-Gon Jinn]] go to Senali with Leed's brother [[Taroon (Rutanian)|Taroon]] where they learn Leed has come to love his foster family and genuinely does not want to leave.

Leed agrees to return to Rutan and speak with his father, but he is kidnapped by a rogue group of Senali called the [[The Ghost Ones|Ghost clan]] before he can. Taroon returns to Rutan while Obi-Wan and Qui-Gon free Leed with help from his foster sister [[Drenna]]. The four of them go to Rutan to stop the war.

Leed tries to convince Frane to make Taroon his heir, but he fails and Frane threatens to keep [[Yaana]], the ten-[[Standard year/Legends|year]]-old daughter of [[Meenon]], in [[Prison/Legends|prison]] until he falls in line. Obi-Wan, Qui-Gon, Leed, and Drenna break Yaana out of prison so Frane has nothing to bargain with.

Frane cuts them off at the landing platform. Leed agrees to stay if Yaana is sent home, and Drenna takes her place as the Senali hostage.

Obi-Wan and Qui-Gon, meanwhile, realize the Ghost clan were actually [[Rutanian]]s sent by Taroon, who wants to be king. They confront him, and he reveals he also planned an attack on the royal kennels. They foil the attack, and Taroon confesses to his father. Impressed, Frane names him his heir and Leed the [[Ambassador/Legends|ambassador]] between their worlds.

==Continuity==
The book's cover features a Photoshopped image of the [[Jabba's Palace/Legends|Jabba's Palace]] denizen [[Loje Nella/Legends|Loje Nella]]. This cannot accurately represent the Rutanian or Senali species, as Loje Nella is full-grown and stands less than 2 meters in height, is non-[[Humanoid/Legends|humanoid]], and far from muscular.

